Last night, I checked the detailed design reports and blueprints of every subsystem.

16
00:01:55,240 --> 00:01:59,400
Dr. Zhao, what's the difference between the currents on flats and slopes?

17
00:01:59,400 --> 00:02:01,400
It's five times the number.

18
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:06,600
   

19
00:02:06,600 --> 00:02:09,000
That's the problem.

20
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:13,200
The most likely cause of this issue is electromagnetic interference.

21
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:21,200
This is the power line of the electric machine.

22
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:23,300
If the current is I,

23
00:02:23,300 --> 00:02:26,000
and this is the hysteresis loop of the Hall effect sensor,

24
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,600
the distance between these two lines is 1.6 mm in standard design.

25
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:34,500
As for our design, the distance is also 1.6 mm.

26
00:02:34,500 --> 00:02:36,100
There is no room for error.

27
00:02:36,100 --> 00:02:38,800
When the current exceeds the set point,

28
00:02:38,800 --> 00:02:43,800
it's possible the electric machine's Hall effect sensor will experience interference.

29
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:47,200
It's entirely possible.

30
00:02:47,200 --> 00:02:49,400
How do we recreate the situation?

31
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,600
We can prove it with a wheel loading test.

32
00:02:57,719 --> 00:02:59,199
The command for slope climbing is sent.

33
00:02:59,200 --> 00:03:02,000
Pay attention to the waveforms and telemetry signals.

34
00:03:05,800 --> 00:03:08,200
The wheel speed is inconsistent.

35
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:11,800
At the same time, the Hall effect sensor is showing spikes.

36
00:03:11,800 --> 00:03:14,400
The electric machine is in PWM mode.

37
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:17,000
The chopper frequency alone is over tens of thousand Hz.

38
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:18,400
I just checked.

39
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:21,800
When we added the weight, the current was over 1000 mA.

40
00:03:21,800 --> 00:03:26,000
The Hall effect sensor and the three-phase line are too close to each other.

41
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,400
That's the reason our Hall effect sensor is showing so many spikes.

42
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:33,800
The next step is to separate the signal line

43
00:03:33,800 --> 00:03:37,600
and the power line in two different directions.

44
00:03:40,400 --> 00:03:41,800
